{"name":"Archive.Wiedijk100Theorems.FriendshipGraphs","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Combinatorics.SimpleGraph.AdjMatrix","Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.Charpoly.FiniteField","Mathlib.Data.Int.ModEq","Mathlib.Data.ZMod.Basic","Mathlib.Tactic.IntervalCases"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L334-L339","name":"Theorems100.friendship_theorem","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.friendship_theorem","doc":"**Friendship theorem**: We wish to show that a friendship graph has a politician (a vertex\nadjacent to all others). We proceed by contradiction, and assume the graph has no politician.\nWe have already proven that a friendship graph with no politician is `d`-regular for some `d`,\nand now we do casework on `d`.\nIf the degree is at most 2, we observe by casework that it has a politician anyway.\nIf the degree is at least 3, the graph cannot exist. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L319-L323","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_le_two","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_le_two","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L311-L316","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_eq_two","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_eq_two","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L295-L308","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.neighborFinset_eq_of_degree_eq_two","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.neighborFinset_eq_of_degree_eq_two","doc":"If `d = 2`, a `d`-regular friendship graph has 3 vertices, so it must be complete graph,\nand all the vertices are politicians. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L273-L290","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_le_one","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.existsPolitician_of_degree_le_one","doc":"If `d ≤ 1`, a `d`-regular friendship graph has at most one vertex, which is\ntrivially a politician. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L243-L268","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.false_of_three_le_degree","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.false_of_three_le_degree","doc":"This is the main proof. Assuming that `3 ≤ d`, we take `p` to be a prime factor of `d-1`.\nThen the `p`th power of the adjacency matrix of a `d`-regular friendship graph must have trace 1\nmod `p`, but we can also show that the trace must be the `p`th power of the trace of the original\nadjacency matrix, which is 0, a contradiction.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L224-L233","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_pow_mod_p_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_pow_mod_p_of_regular","doc":"Modulo a factor of `d-1`, the square and all higher powers of the adjacency matrix\nof a `d`-regular friendship graph reduce to the matrix whose entries are all 1. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L216-L219","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_mul_const_one_mod_p_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_mul_const_one_mod_p_of_regular","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L209-L213","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_mul_const_one_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_mul_const_one_of_regular","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L198-L204","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.card_mod_p_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.card_mod_p_of_regular","doc":"The size of a `d`-regular friendship graph is `1 mod (d-1)`, and thus `1 mod p` for a\nfactor `p ∣ d-1`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L182-L193","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.card_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.card_of_regular","doc":"Let `A` be the adjacency matrix of a `d`-regular friendship graph, and let `v` be a vector\nall of whose components are `1`. Then `v` is an eigenvector of `A ^ 2`, and we can compute\nthe eigenvalue to be `d * d`, or as `d + (Fintype.card V - 1)`, so those quantities must be equal.\n\nThis essentially means that the graph has `d ^ 2 - d + 1` vertices. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L148-L174","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.isRegularOf_not_existsPolitician","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.isRegularOf_not_existsPolitician","doc":"If `G` is a friendship graph without a politician (a vertex adjacent to all others), then\nit is regular. We have shown that nonadjacent vertices of a friendship graph have the same degree,\nand if there isn't a politician, we can show this for adjacent vertices by finding a vertex\nneither is adjacent to, and then using transitivity. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L135-L137","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_mod_p_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_mod_p_of_regular","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L128-L132","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_of_regular","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_of_regular","doc":"Let `A` be the adjacency matrix of a graph `G`.\nIf `G` is a friendship graph, then all of the off-diagonal entries of `A^2` are 1.\nIf `G` is `d`-regular, then all of the diagonal entries of `A^2` are `d`.\nPutting these together determines `A^2` exactly for a `d`-regular friendship graph. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L115-L121","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.degree_eq_of_not_adj","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.degree_eq_of_not_adj","doc":"As `v` and `w` not being adjacent implies\n`degree G v = ((G.adjMatrix R) ^ 3) v w` and `degree G w = ((G.adjMatrix R) ^ 3) v w`,\nthe degrees are equal if `((G.adjMatrix R) ^ 3) v w = ((G.adjMatrix R) ^ 3) w v`\n\nThis is true as the adjacency matrix is symmetric. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L97-L105","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_pow_three_of_not_adj","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_pow_three_of_not_adj","doc":"This calculation amounts to counting the number of length 3 walks between nonadjacent vertices.\nWe use it to show that nonadjacent vertices have equal degrees. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L88-L92","name":"Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_of_ne","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship.adjMatrix_sq_of_ne","doc":"One characterization of a friendship graph is that there is exactly one walk of length 2\nbetween distinct vertices. These walks are counted in off-diagonal entries of the square of\nthe adjacency matrix, so for a friendship graph, those entries are all 1. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L73-L74","name":"Theorems100.ExistsPolitician","kind":"def","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.ExistsPolitician","doc":"A politician is a vertex that is adjacent to all other vertices.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.lean#L67-L68","name":"Theorems100.Friendship","kind":"def","docLink":"./Archive/Wiedijk100Theorems/FriendshipGraphs.html#Theorems100.Friendship","doc":"This property of a graph is the hypothesis of the friendship theorem:\nevery pair of nonadjacent vertices has exactly one common friend,\na vertex to which both are adjacent.\n"}]}